.TH "IDBCursor.direction" "JS" "July 26, 2024" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
IDBCursor.direction \- IDBCursor: direction property
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[B]Note:\f[R] This feature is available in Web Workers.
.PP
The \f[B]\f[CB]direction\f[B]\f[R] read\-only property of the
\f[CR]IDBCursor\f[R] interface is a string that returns the direction of
traversal of the cursor (set using \f[CR]IDBObjectStore.openCursor\f[R]
for example).
See the Value section below for possible values.
.SH VALUE
A string indicating the direction in which the cursor is traversing the
data.
Possible values are:
.TP
\f[B]next\f[R]
This direction causes the cursor to be opened at the start of the
source.
.TP
\f[B]nextunique\f[R]
This direction causes the cursor to be opened at the start of the
source.
For every key with duplicate values, only the first\-visited record
(closest to the start) is yielded.
.TP
\f[B]prev\f[R]
This direction causes the cursor to be opened at the end of the source.
.TP
\f[B]prevunique\f[R]
This direction causes the cursor to be opened at the end of the source.
For every key with duplicate values, only the first\-visited record
(closest to the end) is yielded.
.SH EXAMPLES
In this simple fragment we create a transaction, retrieve an object
store, then use a cursor to iterate through all the records in the
object store.
Within each iteration we log the direction of the cursor.
.RS
.PP
\f[B]Note:\f[R] We can\[cq]t change the direction of travel of the
cursor using the \f[CR]direction\f[R] property, as it is read\-only.
We specify the direction of travel using the 2nd argument of
\f[CR]IDBObjectStore.openCursor\f[R].
.RE
.PP
The cursor does not require us to select the data based on a key; we can
just grab all of it.
Also note that in each iteration of the loop, you can grab data from the
current record under the cursor object using
\f[CR]cursor.value.foo\f[R].
For a complete working example, see our \c
.UR https://github.com/mdn/dom-examples/tree/main/indexeddb-examples/idbcursor
IDBCursor example
.UE \c
\ (\c
.UR https://mdn.github.io/dom-examples/indexeddb-examples/idbcursor/
View the example live
.UE \c
).
.IP
.EX
\f[B]function\f[R] backwards() {
  list.textContent = \[dq]\[dq];
  \f[B]const\f[R] transaction = db.transaction([\[dq]rushAlbumList\[dq]], \[dq]readonly\[dq]);
  \f[B]const\f[R] objectStore = transaction.objectStore(\[dq]rushAlbumList\[dq]);

  objectStore.openCursor(\f[B]null\f[R], \[dq]prev\[dq]).onsuccess = (event) \f[B]=>\f[R] {
    \f[B]const\f[R] cursor = event.target.result;
    \f[B]if\f[R] (cursor) {
      \f[B]const\f[R] listItem = document.createElement(\[dq]li\[dq]);
      listItem.textContent = \[ga]${cursor.value.albumTitle}, ${cursor.value.year}\[ga];
      list.appendChild(listItem);

      console.log(cursor.direction);
      cursor.continue();
    } \f[B]else\f[R] {
      console.log(\[dq]Entries displayed backwards.\[dq]);
    }
  };
}
.EE
